Patient: What type of exercise can I do to help my heart?
Healthcare Educator: Walking is great. Start slow, maybe 10 minutes a day, gradually increase.

Patient: But my neighborhood isn't safe for walking.
Healthcare Educator: You can do indoor exercises. Try marching on the spot or climbing stairs.

Patient: Do I have to exercise every day?
Healthcare Educator: Ideally yes, but start with 3-4 days a week, and slowly increase to daily.

Patient: What if I feel tired while exercising?
Healthcare Educator: It's okay. Rest when needed. Listen to your body and don't overdo it.

Patient: Can I do weight lifting?
Healthcare Educator: Light weights are okay. But avoid heavy lifting as it may strain your heart.

Patient: I don't have weights. What can I use?
Healthcare Educator: You can use household items like water bottles or canned goods as weights.

Patient: Can I do exercises like push-ups?
Healthcare Educator: Start with wall push-ups. If you feel okay, you can gradually try floor push-ups.

Patient: What about sit-ups?
Healthcare Educator: Sit-ups may strain your heart. Try gentle core exercises like standing side bends instead.

Patient: Should I stretch before or after exercising?
Healthcare Educator: Do light warm-up before, and gentle stretching after. It can help prevent injuries.

Patient: What if I get chest pain while exercising?
Healthcare Educator: Stop immediately and rest. If pain persists, seek immediate medical attention.

Patient: Can I drink water during exercise?
Healthcare Educator: Yes, stay hydrated. Drink small sips of water during exercise.

Patient: Can I exercise after eating?
Healthcare Educator: Wait for at least 2 hours after eating before exercising. 

Patient: Can I exercise in the morning or evening?
Healthcare Educator: Both are fine. Choose a time that suits you best.

Patient: How will I know if the exercise is helping?
Healthcare Educator: You'll feel better overall. Also, regular check-ups will show heart improvement.

Patient: Thank you for your help!
Healthcare Educator: You're welcome! Remember, start slow and listen to your body.